\begin_layout Standard
Every desription of bremsstrahlung first describes it by its literal translation
 from german: 
\emph on
braking radiation
\emph default
.
 This gives a general picture of the physics of the phenomena.
 When ionizing radiation is incident upon a material, coulomb interactions
 cause the incident radiation to decelerate.
 During this deceleration, energy is conserved by the emission of electromagneti
c radiation.
 This is enacted physically by a spectrum of gamma and x-ray photos being
 emitted from the target material.
 Bremsstrahlung can be detrimental or useful in real world applications.
 For instance, they often occlude data if a beta emitter is enclosed in
 high Z material, but they are used to generate x-rays for medical diagnostics
 and in other accelerator based sources.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The maximum energy of the emitted radiation can be calculated simply by
 assuming the incoming particle gives up all of its energy in one 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

collision
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{e}=eV=h\nu=\max\left(E_{\gamma}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{e}$
\end_inset

 is the energy of an incident of an electron, 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the charge of the electron, 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the voltage bias applied to generating the electron, 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is Planck's constant, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is the frequency of the photon with energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

.
 This is given (in quantities more commonly used in xray spectroscopy) as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{min}=\frac{hc}{eV}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and is known as the Duane-Hunt law 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Duane1915"

\end_inset

.
 The maximum energy describes a very small percentage of emitted radiation,
 only at very forward angles.
 The rest of the emitted radiation will vary in energy (with many emitted
 at low energy) and direction (with forward bias to high energies).
 Koch and Motz published a review of the spectra from bremsstrahlung with
 varying energy, targets, and directions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
